Predictive Factors of Final Sale Price of Mario Kart Games on Ebay

Cameron Jester

12/20/2020

# Load all necessary packages here:
library(tidyverse)
library(mosaic)
library(moderndive)
library(openintro)

Introduction

Mario Kart was first released in 1992 and since has become a staple in many homes around the world. It only takes two words to send someone into a whirl of nostalgia: Rainbow Road. The revolutionary 3D graphics and 4-player mode of Mario Kart 64 pushed Nintendo into the 21st century gaming market. Over the last _ years, 15 Mario Kart games have been released. Therefore it is no surprise that Nintendo-lovers and racers alike scour the internet to purchase Mario Kart games that are no longer sold on the general market.

This study aims to better understand the relationship between total price paid and the number of bids places on the games. To address this we used a dataset made available by openintro from data on ebay. The data was collected in October of 2009.

What is the relationship between the number of bids at auction and the total price paid for MarioKart games on Ebay? Do these relationships depend on the condition of the game?

Each case in the dataset is one of 143 sold games. and includes two types of conditions new and used. The main outcome variable of interest in this study is the games total price paid, with two explanatory variables: number of bids and condition. Each of the two numerical variables were measured in millimeters (mm). It is important to note that Ebay offers a buy now option that is not included in the used data set. Of the original sample size of 143 games, only one game was missing a title when sold on ebay. The only missing value among the mariokart data set is a title of a game sold. Although,there was a stock photo included with the game which most like had the game title. This does not effect our data. An outlier was present in the mariokart data set. We removed the outlier to better reflect the analysis in which this project explores. The function filter(mariokart, total_pr < 300) removed data points in which the price paid was over $300.

mariokart = filter(mariokart, total_pr < 300)

A colored scatterplot was constructed to display the relationship between the three variables in Figure 4. In this plot we can see that used condition games tend to have a lower price paid but similar number of bids overall compared to new condition games. Interestingly, when controlling for the game conditions, the direction of the new condition games, the relationship between price and bids flips to the negative direction. While the overall relationship between price and bids was positive (and not very strong), when controlling for conditions these relationships are not only opposite to one another but are also more strongly linear. Thus when building a regression model, controlling for game conditions will be critical.

Statistical Inference

3.1 Methods

The components of our multiple linear regression model are the following:

  • Outcome variable y = Total Price Paid (in U.S. dollars)
  • Numerical explanatory variable x1 = Number of Bids
  • Categorical explanatory variable x2 = Condition of Game

3.2 Model Results

Table 2. Regression table of linear model of bill depth as a function of flipper length and penguin species.

mariokart_model = lm(total_pr ~ n_bids + cond, data = mariokart)
get_regression_table(mariokart_model)
term estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
intercept 53.669 2.351 22.831 0.000 49.021 58.316
n_bids 0.007 0.141 0.052 0.959 -0.271 0.285
condused -9.981 1.666 -5.992 0.000 -13.274 -6.688

3.3 Interpreting the regression table

We can interpret the estimated coefficients in the linear model as follows:

  • The intercept (53.67) represents the average price paid for new games with a number of 0 bids. This does not make sense in context, because games cannot be sold with 0 bids as our data set excludes games that had no bids, which is better known as the buy now option on Ebay. Furthermore, the smallest number of bids in our data set is 1 bid.

  • The estimate for the slope for number of bids (0.007) is the associated change in the average total price paid depending on number of bids, for a fixed condition. Based on this estimate, for a fixed condition, for every 1 increase in number of bids, there was an associated increase in total price paid by by 0.007 dollars, on average.

  • The estimates for the coefficients of condused is the offset in the intercept relative to the reference condition, New (for a fixed number of bids). In other words, for a fixed number of bids, the average total price paid of used games is 9.981 dollars lower relative to games of new condition.

3.4 Inference for multiple regression

Using the output of our regression table well test the null hypothesis for our numerical explanatory variable. The null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between a games number of bids and total price paid at the population level (the population slope is zero).

  • H_0: beta_bids = 0; H_A: beta_bids 0

There appears to be a positive relationship between the number of bids and price paid after controlling for condition, (slope of 0.007). Furthermore, this does not appear to be a meaningful relationship because in Table 2 we see;

  • the 95% confidence interval for the population slope is (-0.271, 0.285), both on the negative and positive side, which means our CI includes 0 (our null value), indicating little difference in our tested groups.
  • the p-value (.959) is rather large, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the population slope is zero in favor of the alternative.

So taking into account potential sampling variation in results (for example if we collected similar data for a different group of games) the relationship between bids and price does appear to be positive, after controlling for condition.

We can also see that the coefficients for the condition levels are statistically significant and include confidence intervals entirely on the negative side, which means that, after controlling for number of bids, used games have average total price paid that are significantly different from those of new games (i.e., each coefficient is significantly different from zero).

3.5 Residual Analysis

We conducted a residual analysis to see if there was any systematic pattern of residuals for the statistical model we ran. If there are systematic patterns, then we cannot fully trust our confidence intervals and p-values above.

Our residual analysis consisted of (1) a residual histogram to check for normality of the residuals, (2) a scatterplot of residuals against the fitted (predicted) values, (3) a scatterplot of the residuals against number of bids, and (4) side-by-side boxplots of the residuals for both game conditions.

residual_table = get_regression_points(mariokart_model)

gf_histogram( ~ residual, color = "red", fill = "steelblue", data = residual_table) + 
  labs(x = "Residuals", y = "Number of Bids") + 
  theme_minimal()

While the linear model of residuals was skewed right(Figure 5), there appears to be systematic patterns in each of the residual scatter/boxplots. In the scatterplot of residuals against fitted values (Figure 6), there is a clear pattern in variability among residuals for fitted values (predicted values of total price paid) that are tightly packed around 44.25 and 53.75. This could mean there is a disruption in residuals against our analysis. This corresponds with the scatterplot of the residuals against number of bids (Figure 7), which shows a higher degree of variability among the residuals for bids under 25 with few patterns or disruptions. The boxplots of the residuals against conditions (Figure 8) inform how these departures from constant variability might arise, with the new condition games showing almost identical variability in the residuals compared to used condition games. A residual table was included to better identify residuals for the data as there is a pattern identified in the residual plot.

{width = 50%}

4. Conclusions

We found that there was not a significant association between number of bids and total price paid among Mario Kart games on Ebay. After controlling for game conditions, new condition games were associated with significantly higher total price paid, on average, yet Figure 4 shows that new condition games had fewer bids than used games. The linear model indicated that, after controlling for conditions, each additional bid was associated with an average increase in price of about 0.007 dollars. This, however, does not mean that changes in the number of bids cause changes in total price paid, merely that they are slightly associated. Analysis of the 95% Confidence Interval and p-value led us to fail to reject the null value of 0, which favors a low significance between the two categories.

Overall, these findings suggest that game conditions are not all equal and are associated with different characteristics. Future work could involve focusing more on new condition games in particular, to see what other factors might explain the few amounts of bids overall.It would be interesting to see how games that were bought under the buy now option (meaning 0 bids) compares to the condition and total price paid for Mario Kart games. For those interested in purchasing Mario Kart games on Ebay, it is important to take into consideration how many bids have been placed compared to the condition as this could indicate how much you will pay. No matter what, always remember, all models are wrong but some are useful! * * *
